		   <tr><td valign="top" id="fs8" class="mform2" ><span id="notbold">By:</span> <a href="/db/poster.html?user=1286"><span id=Encyclopedia>gbaji</span></a><b><span id=Encyclopedia><br>Encyclopedia</span></b><br /><img src="/shared/user_star_ico.gif" height="9" width="9" alt="*" /><img src="/shared/user_star_ico.gif" height="9" width="9" alt="*"/><img src="/shared/user_star_ico.gif" height="9" width="9" alt="*"/><img src="/shared/user_star_ico.gif" height="9" width="9" alt="*" /><br />9879 posts
		   <br /><nobr><span id="notbold">Score</span>: Good [4.03]</nobr><br /><br /><a href="/cgi-bin/pm.pl?action=addtolist&addname=gbaji&type=Address" id="fs8"><img src="/shared/plus.gif" border="0" align="middle" height="9" width="9" alt="Add to address book"> Add to address book</a><br /><img src="/shared/transp.gif" width="135" border="0" height="1"></td><td valign="top" class="mform2" width="100%"><p><blockquote><b class="sm">elorianBLAH wrote:</b><hr size="1" /><blockquote><b class="sm">Quote:</b><hr size="1" />We will fix Manaburn. Our preferred method is to uncap the ability and implement a cap based on the maximum percentage of health you can do in a single hit. So one of you, facing a million hit point boss mob (fairly common in today’s game) can expect a full manaburn to land for 10s of thousands of points of damage in one hit. <br /><hr size="1" /></blockquote><br /><br />gbaji&nbsp;&nbsp;are you with me when i saw IT'S ABOUT ****ING TIME!!!!!!!!!!!!!!!!!!!!!!!!!!!!!!!!!<br /> <hr size="1" /></blockquote><br /><br />Lol. Yeah. Although my wiz doesn't have it (not really close to it anyway since I've played him like 5 times in the last year), but they definately need to do *something* with MB.<br /><br />Their problem is that they couldn't decide on how to use the ability and kept vacillating. On the one hand, there's the utility in being able to just instantly blast a single mob. There's some argument that MB can allow a wizard to blow all his mana to kill a single exp level mob instantly. While not incredibly useful (cause most of the time that's a waste), it addes the the group wizards &quot;oh sh*t&quot; management ability. It's why you want a wizard in your group after all, to quickly deal with adds that the group can't manage.<br /><br />On the other hand, is the mini/boss aspect of MB. They clearly didn't want teams of MB wizards to just casually nuke dragons (which was the original problem with the ability). Kunark era dragons were capped at 32k hps. That allowed a small number of wizards with MB to instantly kill any dragon in the game instantly and with zero risk. Not a good thing.<br /><br />They decided on the casting cap because they wanted to preserve MBs single target capability, while removing it's incredibly capability with dragon killing. And it wasn't a bad solution to be honest. However, the game has changed dramatically since then. HP caps on mobs have been lifted (with a vengeance). Today, people single group mobs for exp with as many or more HPs then those old dragons had. Heck. I can casually solo mobs with 10k+ hps and I'm a paladin!<br /><br />The overpowered nature of MB in terms of single target killing really isn't an issue anymore IMO. There are many much more efficient ways to kill mobs then MB, and those old dragons are all single groupable nowadays anyway, so that's not an issue anymore (gotta love itemization inflation!). MB has for some time *only* really had a use in terms of raid functionality. Losing the ability to insta-kill a 15k HP mob is a small price to pay to allow a group of wizards to do massive MB damage to boss level mobs (which is what it sounds like they're doing). Capping based on max percent prevents it from being used as an instant or over-kill of lower hp mobs, but allows multiple wizards to use the ability to great effect potentially in raid encounters.<br /><br />We'll have to see how that works out though. Unfortunately, a bar of mana is still going to more efficiently be spent just cast normally, so I'm not sure how much impact this will really have. It may allow raids to be able to pick and choose when/where to MB in order to kill a particular mob quickly. It'll be situational, but at least it wont be more or less completely useless as it is now...</p></td></td></tr><tr><td colspan="2" class="mform2"><table border="0" cellspacing="0" cellpadding="0" width="100%"><tr><td id="fs8">Posting from San Diego, CA</td></tr></table>
